Let's consider a project that is represented by a weighted directed graph $G(V,E)$, where $V$ is the set of tasks in the project, $E$ is the set of dependencies between tasks, and the weight of an edge $(i,j)$ represents the time it takes to complete task $j$ after task $i$ has been completed. 

A project manager wants to find the shortest possible time to complete all tasks in the project. However, due to resource constraints, there is also a maximum total weight of edges that the project manager can include in the project. 

If the total weight of all edges in $G$ is $W$, the project manager decides to reduce the total weight to $R$ by removing some edges from $G$. After the removal of these edges, the resulting graph must still be a directed acyclic graph (DAG).

Let $D_i$ be the shortest path from a special start vertex $s$ to vertex $i$ in the resulting graph. The project manager would like to maximize the minimum value of $D_i$ over all vertices $i$.

Formally, the project manager's problem can be formulated as:

\begin{equation*}
\begin{aligned}
& \underset{G'}{\text{maximize}}
& & \min_{i \in V} D_i \\
& \text{subject to}
& & \text{total weight of edges in } G' \leq R, \\
&&& G' \text{ is a DAG}, \\
&&& G' \text{ is a subgraph of } G.
\end{aligned}
\end{equation*}

Given the graph $G$, the weight of each edge, and the maximum total weight $R$, can you find the optimal graph $G'$?
